"a.清澈的，晴朗的，安静的 无 无 无 serene (adj.)  mid-15c., ""clear, calm,"" from Latin serenus ""peaceful, calm, clear"" (of weather), figuratively ""cheerful, glad, tranquil,"" of uncertain origin; perhaps from a suffixed variant of PIE *ksero- ""dry,"" source of Greek xeros ""dry"" (see xerasia). In English, applied to persons since 1630s. Related: Serenely."
